{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17601574","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17601574"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T12:15:33+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T12:15:33+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15659"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15659","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15659"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.35,0.2,0.25,0.1,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8350"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71109"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8350","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8350"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15659"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56580"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4949"},{"type":"tags","id":"7004"},{"type":"tags","id":"8576"},{"type":"tags","id":"8702"},{"type":"tags","id":"10109"},{"type":"tags","id":"10118"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20135"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20138"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71109","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/71109"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring embryological development, the pituitary gland develops from two distinct tissues. The anterior pituitary forms from an upward growth of oral ectoderm, whereas the posterior pituitary forms from a downward growth of neural tissue from the diencephalon.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following structures is a remnant of Rathke\u0027s pouch?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Neurohypophysis","Pars tuberalis","Hypothalamic infundibulum","Pars nervosa","Median eminence"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ERathke\u0027s pouch forms from oral ectoderm and develops into the anterior pituitary (adenohypophysis). The \u003Cstrong\u003Epars tuberalis\u003C/strong\u003E is a thin sleeve of tissue that wraps around the pituitary stalk and is derived from Rathke\u0027s pouch.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eneurohypophysis\u003C/strong\u003E, \u003Cstrong\u003Ehypothalamic infundibulum\u003C/strong\u003E, \u003Cstrong\u003Emedian eminence\u003C/strong\u003E, and \u003Cstrong\u003Epars nervosa\u003C/strong\u003E all develop from neural ectoderm of the diencephalon, specifically from a downward growth called the infundibulum. These structures are therefore not remnants of Rathke\u0027s pouch.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe pars tuberalis, pars distalis and pars intermedia make up the adenohypophysis, which is derived from Rathke\u0027s pouch.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Rathke\u0027s pouch is an embryological structure that develops from oral ectoderm and forms the anterior pituitary gland","The pars tuberalis develops from Rathke\u0027s pouch and wraps around the pituitary stalk","The posterior pituitary develops separately from neural ectoderm of the diencephalon"],"references":["Hormone supply to the pituitary gland: A comprehensive investigation of female\u2011related tumors (Review). Int J Mol Med. 2022 Oct;50(4):122. doi: 10.3892/ijmm.2022.5178. Epub 2022 Aug 10. PMID: 35946461; PMCID: PMC9387558","Melmed, S., Polonsky, K. S., Larsen, P. R., \u0026 Kronenberg, H. M. (2015). Williams textbook of endocrinology E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Clark, O. H., Duh, Q. Y., Kebebew, E., Gosnell, J. E., \u0026 Shen, W. T. (Eds.). (2016). Textbook of endocrine surgery. JP Medical Ltd","Young, W. F. (2011). Netter\u0027s Endocrine System: Netter Collection of Medical Illustrations: Endocrine System E-book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Wass, J. A., \u0026 Stewart, P. M. (Eds.). (2011). Oxford textbook of endocrinology and diabetes. Oxford University Press, USA"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56580"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15659"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56580","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/56580"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-17T00:10:43+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-17T00:11:27+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8350"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71109"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4929","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/a